    <Callout type="info">
      <strong>A note on naming:</strong> Independent sources do not agree on what to call the tiers above Community Builders. Some describe a separate "Mega Builders" tier around $99/month and a "Team Builders" tier around $199/month; others describe "Team Builders" as a single ~$997 lifetime step above Community Builders. This isn't a mistake on any one source's part — OLSP has renamed and restructured these tiers across platform relaunches. Don't expect a single canonical ladder above Community Builders; verify the current name, contents, and price directly at checkout before buying.
    </Callout>

    <Callout type="warn">
      <strong>We have not reviewed VIP, Elite, or Elite Plus.</strong> These three tiers, reported at roughly $6,500, $15,000, and $25,000, surfaced during our research but are not covered by any of the five in-depth OLSP reviews on this site. We're stating that they exist and their reported price range — we are not recommending them, ranking them, or vouching for what they include. If you're offered one of these on a call, get the full terms in writing before deciding.
    </Callout>
  </section>

  <section id="decision-framework">
    <h2>3. Which OLSP Product Should You Buy First? A Decision Framework</h2>
    <p>The mistake most upsell-overwhelm complaints describe is treating the ladder above as "tier 1, tier 2, tier 3" — buy the next one up when you can afford it. That's not how these products actually work. Each one solves a different bottleneck, and buying the wrong one for your situation is the single most common way people end up feeling like OLSP is "just upsells." Start by asking what's actually stopping you, then match it to the table below.</p>

    <div class="table-scroll">
    <table>
      <tr><th>If your bottleneck is...</th><th>Consider</th><th>Why</th></tr>
      <tr><td>"I don't have traffic or an audience yet"</td><td>Stay at Megalink. Use the free Bootcamp training first.</td><td>Live Profit Builders and Community Builders both require an existing audience to generate meaningful income — buying either before this point is the most common source of upsell regret.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>"I have a funnel but need faster traffic to test it"</td><td>OLSP Solo Ads, as a bounded, one-time test</td><td>Solo Ads is a traffic cost, not a training product — only worth it once you already have somewhere for that traffic to go.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>"I'm earning something at Megalink and want event-based commissions"</td><td>Live Profit Builders (~$49/month)</td><td>This tier is designed to be added after you've validated results at Megalink, not as an automatic next step for everyone.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>"I'm active, want to build a team, and use Facebook heavily"</td><td>Community Builders (~$197/month)</td><td>Only worth it if all three are true: you're already promoting, you can commit 30+ minutes a day, and you're comfortable with Facebook-centric training. Skip it if any one of those doesn't apply.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>"I'm Facebook-active and my bottleneck is time, not leads"</td><td>MineeMe ($27/month), evaluated on its own</td><td>A parallel tool, not a ladder rung — only relevant if you're already posting consistently and want to reduce manual engagement time.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>"I've been on Community Builders for 5+ months and plan to stay"</td><td>Compare against Team Builders' lifetime price</td><td>Roughly five months of Community Builders at ~$197/month approaches the ~$997 lifetime Team Builders price — worth doing the math if you're committed long-term.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>"I'm being offered VIP, Elite, or Elite Plus"</td><td>Pause before buying</td><td>No review on this site covers these tiers. Treat a four- or five-figure upgrade with the same caution you'd apply to any major purchase, regardless of how it's presented on the call.</td></tr>
    </table>
    </div>

    <p>Two filters apply on top of the table above, not instead of it:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Budget filters within your matched bottleneck — it doesn't override it.</strong> If your bottleneck is "no audience yet," a bigger budget doesn't make Community Builders the right choice; it still requires an audience Community Builders itself won't build for you.</li>
      <li><strong>Time availability is a hard gate for Community Builders specifically.</strong> Every source we found — the site's own review and independent commentary alike — agrees this tier's recurring cost only pays off with sustained daily activity. Treat the 30-minutes-a-day commitment as a yes/no question before buying, not a soft suggestion.</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

